Fine Arts Community Concert - Monday\, October 1st  6:30PM - 8:00PM
Bell's Fine Arts Committee is very excited to present No-No Boy\, an indie-folk duo whose music is based on their own doctoral research on Asian-American stories of World War II incarceration and the immigration of refugees from Vietnam.  Their multimedia concert is musically moving\, rich in content\, entertaining and inspiring.  This event is free and open to the public so please save the date and feel free to invite your friends and family. Suggested for middle school and high school ages and adults.

Join us for a fantastic night of entertainment to benefit Bell School.
15% of all proceeds will be donated back to Bell.  Enjoy a family dinner at Meatheads.
Potbelly's will donate 25% of all sales back to Bell.  Enjoy a sandwich for dinner!

The Holiday Market for grades Pre-K thru 5th will be held on Friday\, December 12th.  The majority of the items at the market will be priced between $1 and $7.  We recommend that the students bring their money in a sealed envelope with their name and room number on the front and the individuals they are purchasing for on the back (mom\, dad\, sister\, brother\, grandma\, etc.).  Students in grades 6th  8th will have an opportunity at the end of the day to shop if their schedule allows.  If possible please send in small bills (1s and 5s).

Please join us in the Auditorium for SPEAKER NIGHT AT BELL SCHOOL on THURSDAY\, DECEMBER 4\, 2014 at 6:30 pm.  Karen Jacobson and Lauren Bondy\, of Parenting Perspectives\, will return with their energy and insight to present: 'What's So Big About Self-Esteem?'  Come learn the essential ingredients for fostering true self-esteem in your children.  The workshop will define what self-esteem really means\; offer specific tips and strategies for nurturing this important quality in our children\; debunk the myths of self-esteem\; and relay common traps adults often fall into while trying to raise a 'happy' child.

Sign Language classes for parents will begin on Friday\, November 14 at 9 a.m. in the school auditorium. Ms. Ashley Brockway\, our ASL teacher\, will conduct the classes.  We look forward to seeing everyone there!

Doors open at 5:30 pm with pizza\, snacks and drinks all available for sale in the school cafeteria. Movie starts at 6:30 pm. Come dressed as your favorite character! Frozen tattoos and glow sticks will also be for sale. 

Tickets are $5 per person in advance and $6 at the door. Order forms were sent home via backpack mail.
Come and learn about all of the different high school opportunities in Chicago.  Public and private schools will be represented.

Family Fine Arts/Green Night -\nCreate\, reuse\, recyle\, repurpose....UPCYCLE!  Bell's Fine Arts and Green Committees are pleased to present an evening of artistic and ecological fun for the whole family on Thursday\, April 24th from 6 to 8 PM.  Explore new ways to use old things - turn trash into art\, find out how a swing set can be a musical instrument\, and put your own energy to use on a "Working Bikes" bike machine.  Learn about worm composting\, keeping bees on urban rooftops\, and raising chickens in the city.  Help create gardens in surprising places with seed bombs. Enjoy Imagination Theatre's interactive show\, "Go Green" as well as performances by the Bell Choir and Bell Band. Find out about the latest activities of the Conservation Club and the Service Learning Group and join Ms. Clancy's drum circle. You can even donate your old bike (working or non-working) and help Working Bikes change lives\, trade in an old toy at the toy exchange\, or bring donations for the gently-used/extra school supply drive. Come early for the return of Food Truck Frenzy!  and enjoy gourmet sandwiches\, burgers\, pizza\, cupcakes and other delectable treats from \n4 to 6 PM.  Connect with other Bell Families and the planet at UPCYCLE!
